# [MPLS](../wg/mpls.html)

## Summary
The MPLS Working Group met at IETF 125 to discuss the status of active documents, specifically focusing on MPLS Network Action (MNA) extensions, Network Resource Partition (NRP) signaling, and OAM enhancements. Key highlights included the advancement of the MNA post-stack data (PSD) solutions, proposed extensions to RSVP-TE for Fast Reroute (FRR) optimization, and refinements to OAM procedures for NRPs.

## Key Discussion Points

### WG Status Update
**Adrian Farrel** provided the status update ([Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-mpls-01-wg-status-update-01)). 
- **Draft Status:** `draft-ietf-mpls-mna-ps-hdr` is with the RFC Editor. Two other documents are with the IESG.
- **New Adoptions:** Four documents were recently adopted as working group drafts.
- **Errata:** An errata was filed regarding IPv6 unnumbered interfaces; **Kireeti Kompella** agreed to initiate discussion on the mailing list to clarify the technical details.

### Carrying NRP related Information in MPLS Packets
**Jie Dong** presented on carrying NRP information using MNA Post-Stack Data (PSD) ([Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-mpls-02-carrying-nrp-related-information-in-mpls-packets-00)). 
- **Document:** [draft-ietf-mpls-mna-psd-nrp-selector](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-mpls-mna-psd-nrp-selector/)
- **Technical Content:** The draft defines a 32-bit NRP Selector ID within the PSD to allow transit nodes to perform NRP-specific processing. This is intended to be complementary to In-Stack Data (ISD) approaches.
- **Discussion:** 
    - **Joel Halpern** suggested changing the title to explicitly mention "MNA post-stack data."
    - **Pawan Beeram** questioned the necessity of the "ancillary data" field; Jie Dong clarified it is for future extensions like statistics or egress monitoring.
    - **Jim Guichard** asked why a 32-bit selector was chosen over smaller existing stack fields. Jie Dong explained this aligns with 3GPP network slice identifiers for easier mapping.

### STAMP Extensions for Reflecting STAMP Packet MPLS Extension Headers
**Rakesh Gandhi** presented extensions for the Simple Two-way Active Measurement Protocol (STAMP) ([Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-mpls-stamp-extensions-for-reflecting-stamp-packet-mpls-extension-headers-00)).
- **Context:** Related to [draft-ietf-mpls-stamp](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-mpls-stamp/).
- **Technical Content:** The proposal allows a STAMP Session Reflector to copy MNA headers (ISD or PSD) from a received packet into a STAMP TLV in the response. This supports hop-by-hop telemetry (e.g., IOAM) measurement.
- **Next Steps:** The authors are seeking review from the MPLS WG and adoption in the IPPM WG.

### BGP-LS and IPFIX Extensions for MNA
**Jie Dong** presented two cross-area topics:
1. **BGP-LS for SR Policies:** [Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-mpls-04-supplement-of-bgp-ls-distribution-for-sr-policies-and-state-00). This draft (in IDR) proposes reporting MNA information via BGP-LS. **Tarek Saad** inquired if there was a use case for reporting general MPLS Label Stack Entries (LSEs) rather than just MNA; Jie Dong noted that outside of MNA, there are currently few drivers for reporting non-zero TC/TTL fields via BGP-LS.
2. **IPFIX for MNA:** [Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-mpls-05-export-of-mpls-network-action-mna-information-in-ipfix-00). This draft (in OPSAWG) defines new Information Elements for exporting MNA in-stack and post-stack data.

### Signaling Optimization Objective and Bounded Metrics for MPLS Fast Reroute
**Pawan Beeram** presented a new proposal for RSVP-TE FRR ([Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-mpls-06-signaling-optimization-objective-and-bounded-metrics-for-mpls-fast-reroute-backup-lsp-tunnels-00)).
- **Technical Content:** The draft introduces a "Fast-Reroute Extension" object to allow the ingress node to signal specific optimization objectives (e.g., minimize delay) and bounded metrics for backup path computation.
- **Discussion:**
    - **Adrian Farrel** noted similarities to PCEP (PCEP Objective Functions) and recommended checking for consistency or shared registries.
    - **Tarek Saad** raised concerns regarding backup path sharing on a Point of Local Repair (PLR) if different primary LSPs request different optimization objectives. Pawan Beeram noted this essentially creates multiple backup path profiles.
    - **Kireeti Kompella** asked if this would extend to other constraints like affinity or bandwidth. Pawan Beeram confirmed that while the object is extensible, the focus is on basic metrics missing from the current Fast-Reroute object.

### OAM for Network Resource Partition (NRP) in MPLS Networks
**Liuyan Han** presented updates on NRP OAM ([Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-mpls-07-operations-administration-and-maintenance-oam-for-network-resource-partition-nrp-in-mpls-network-01)).
- **Technical Content:** Updates include refined error codes for diagnosing NRP-specific failures in LSP Ping and Traceroute.
- **Discussion:**
    - **Tony Li** questioned the definition of "NRP resource unavailable," suggesting that if an NRP is provisioned, the resources (like queues) should be available to accept OAM packets.
    - **Tarek Saad** suggested further splitting error codes to distinguish between "NRP ID not recognized" and "NRP ID not configured."

